Certainly! To **add syntax highlighting where every word or sentence inside "double quotes" or 'single quotes' is red**, you need to post-process the rendered HTML from markdown.

A simple, efficient place to do this is by overriding the [text renderer](https://marked.js.org/using_pro#renderer) in the `MarkdownBlock.renderer`. We'll look for quoted text and wrap it in a `<span class="md-quote">...</span>`, then inject the needed CSS into the component.

Here's **what you need to change**. In summary:

1. **Add a new `.md-quote` style to turn text red.**
2. **Override the renderer's `text` function to wrap quoted words/sentences.**

Below is the modified code for `MarkdownBlock` including these steps (only the relevant part is changed for brevity):

```js
export class MarkdownBlock extends MarkdownElement {
	constructor() {
		super();
	}

	connectedCallback() {
		super.connectedCallback();

		// Inject quote-highlighting CSS if not present
		if(!document.getElementById("md-block-quote-css")) {
			const style = document.createElement("style");
			style.id = "md-block-quote-css";
			style.textContent = `
				.md-quote { color: red; }
			`;
			document.head.appendChild(style);
		}
	}

	_parse () {
		return marked.parse(this._mdContent);
	}

	static renderer = Object.assign({
		text(text) {
			// Regex for "quoted text" or 'quoted text'
			// Handles nested, multi-word, etc
			return text.replace(
				/(["'])(.+?)\1/g,
				(match, quote, content) =>
					`${quote}<span class="md-quote">${content}</span>${quote}`
			);
		},

		heading (text, level, _raw, slugger) {
			level = Math.min(6, level + (this.hmin - 1));
			const id = slugger.slug(text);
			const hlinks = this.hlinks;

			let content;

			if (hlinks === null) {
				// No heading links
				content = text;
			}
			else {
				content = `<a href="#${id}" class="anchor">`;

				if (hlinks === "") {
					// Heading content is the link
					content += text + "</a>";
				}
				else {
					// Headings are prepended with a linked symbol
					content += hlinks + "</a>" + text;
				}
			}

			return `<h${level} id="${id}">${content}</h${level}>`;
		},

		code (code, language, escaped) {
			if (this._contentFromHTML) {
				code = code.replace(/&amp;(?=[lg]t;)/g, "&");
			}
			else {
				code = code.replace(/</g, "&lt;");
			}

			return `<pre class="language-${language}"><code>${code}</code></pre>`;
		}
	}, MarkdownSpan.renderer);

	// ... rest of MarkdownBlock ...
}
```

**Summary of changes:**
- Added a `text(text)` renderer method to wrap quoted content in a red `<span>`.
- Injected a style block if not already present.
- Only this part needs to go in your `MarkdownBlock` definition; the rest of the code remains unchanged.

**How it works:**  
Any `"word"` or `'sentence'` in your markdown will appear **red** in the resulting HTML because it's wrapped with a `.md-quote` style.

