Certainly! You can create a production-ready ExpandableText component in React Native. This component displays **one line with "See more"** appended if the text is longer than one line, and when "See more" is tapped, it expands to show the **full text**.

Below is a complete component. You can customize the styling as needed.

---

**ExpandableText.js**
```jsx
import React, { useState, useRef } from 'react';
import { Text, TouchableOpacity, StyleSheet, View } from 'react-native';

const ExpandableText = ({
  text,
  seeMoreText = ' See more',
  seeLessText = ' See less',
  seeMoreTextStyle = {},
  textStyle = {},
}) => {
  const [isExpanded, setIsExpanded] = useState(false);
  const [showSeeMore, setShowSeeMore] = useState(false);
  const [textLayouted, setTextLayouted] = useState(false);

  // Only run on first layout
  const _onTextLayout = (e) => {
    if (!textLayouted) {
      setTextLayouted(true);
      const lines = e.nativeEvent.lines;
      if (lines.length > 1) setShowSeeMore(true);
    }
  };

  return (
    <View>
      <Text
        style={textStyle}
        numberOfLines={isExpanded ? undefined : 1}
        ellipsizeMode="tail"
        onTextLayout={_onTextLayout}
      >
        {text}
        {!isExpanded && showSeeMore ? (
          <Text
            style={[styles.seeMore, seeMoreTextStyle]}
            onPress={() => setIsExpanded(true)}
            suppressHighlighting={true}
          >
            {seeMoreText}
          </Text>
        ) : null}
      </Text>
      {/* (Optional) add see less */}
      {isExpanded && showSeeMore ? (
        <TouchableOpacity onPress={() => setIsExpanded(false)}>
          <Text style={[styles.seeMore, seeMoreTextStyle]}>{seeLessText}</Text>
        </TouchableOpacity>
      ) : null}
    </View>
  );
};


const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  seeMore: {
    color: '#2e78b7',
    fontWeight: 'bold',
  },
});

export default ExpandableText;
```

---

**Usage Example:**
```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { View } from 'react-native';
import ExpandableText from './ExpandableText';

export default function App() {
  return (
    <View style={{ padding: 16 }}>
      <ExpandableText
        text="This is a very long text that will get truncated and show 'See more' if it doesn't fit in a single line. Try expanding this to see the full content. It's perfect for user bios, descriptions, or anywhere text may be too long."
      />
    </View>
  );
}
```

---

### Features covered:

- Only shows "See more" if the text exceeds 1 line.
- "See more" appears at the end of the first line.
- Full text is shown on expand.
- Optionally, user can see "See less" to collapse (you can remove this part if not desired).
- Customizable via props (styling/text for "See more"/"See less").
- Production ready: efficient, stateless where possible, works with all lengths of text.

**Note:**  
The truncation and calling `onTextLayout` is the standard way in React Native to know the number of lines. This implementation is robust for both iOS and Android.

