answer:
You are using a **Trie** (prefix tree) for prefix queries, currently implemented as:

```cpp
struct Node{
    vector<Node*> node;
    int cnt;

    Node(){
        node.resize(26,NULL);
        cnt =0;
    }
};
```

This has **wasted memory**, because every node always allocates a `vector<Node*>(26)` regardless of how many children it actually has. In English: every (possibly leaf) node always allocates storage for all 26 possible children, the majority of which are unused.

### How to make it more memory efficient?

#### **Variant 1: Use unordered_map**

Instead of `vector<Node*> node`, use `unordered_map<char, Node*> node;` so only required edges exist.

```cpp
#include <unordered_map>

struct Node{
    std::unordered_map<char, Node*> node;
    int cnt;

    Node(){
        cnt = 0;
    }
};
```

And adjust code:

```cpp
    int child_ind = s[ind] -'a';
    if(!root->node.count(s[ind])) root->node[s[ind]] = new Node();
    root->node[s[ind]]->cnt++;
    insert(root->node[s[ind]], ind+1, s);
```

And similarly in `queryPrefix`:

```cpp
    if (ind == s.length()) return root->cnt;
    if(!root->node.count(s[ind])) return root->cnt;
    return (root->cnt + queryPrefix(root->node[s[ind]],ind+1,s));
```

#### **Variant 2: Use Array of Pointers Only On Demand**

Alternatively, if speed is critical and you want to avoid the hash overhead, you can use:
- a `Node* node[26]` initialized to `nullptr`
- But do *not* allocate the array dynamically; you just store 26 pointers per node. It is more memory than `unordered_map` in worst case, but no dynamic memory for the pointer array, and no hash-table overhead.

```cpp
struct Node{
    Node* node[26];
    int cnt;

    Node(){
        memset(node, 0, sizeof(node));
        cnt =0;
    }
};
```

This is already more efficient than std::vector (because `vector` has capacity and pointer overhead); but still, `unordered_map` is most memory efficient for sparse branches.

#### **Variant 3: Children Only As Needed**

If you are targeting very low memory usage and your data is *very sparse*, you could store child pointers as a vector<pair<char, Node*> > and use binary search per lookup. But unordered_map is easier and close in practice.

---

### **Updated Example: unordered_map Version**

```cpp
#include <unordered_map>

struct Node {
    std::unordered_map<char, Node*> node;
    int cnt;
    Node(): cnt(0) {}
    ~Node() {
        for (auto& p : node) delete p.second;
    }
};

class Trie {
    Node* root;
public:
    Trie() { root = new Node(); }
    ~Trie() { delete root; }
    void insert(const std::string& s) {
        Node* curr = root;
        for (char c : s) {
            if (!curr->node.count(c))
                curr->node[c] = new Node();
            curr = curr->node[c];
            curr->cnt++;
        }
    }
    int queryPrefix(const std::string& s) {
        Node* curr = root;
        int total = 0;
        for (char c : s) {
            if (!curr->node.count(c))
                break;
            curr = curr->node[c];
            total += curr->cnt;
        }
        return total;
    }
};
```

**Rest of your code can remain the same!**

---

### **Takeaway**

- Use `unordered_map<char, Node*>` instead of `vector<Node*>` for maximum memory savings with sparse data.
- You can use a fixed array `Node* node[26]` for modest gains and faster lookup.
- Use a vector of pairs only if you expect *very* high sparsity and are okay with O(log N) lookup.

---

**If you want a drop-in replacement for your code, the unordered_map version above will cut the memory usage drastically for most realistic word sets.**

