Certainly! Here’s a simple `Events` class in JavaScript that allows you to subscribe to events, unsubscribe, and trigger them as per your requirements.

```js
class Events {
    constructor() {
        this._events = {};  // Stores eventName: [callback1, callback2...]
    }

    subscribe(eventName, callback) {
        if (!this._events[eventName]) {
            this._events[eventName] = [];
        }
        this._events[eventName].push(callback);
    }

    unsubscribe(eventName, callback) {
        if (!this._events[eventName]) return;
        this._events[eventName] = this._events[eventName].filter(cb => cb !== callback);
        // Remove key if empty to avoid leaks
        if (this._events[eventName].length === 0) {
            delete this._events[eventName];
        }
    }

    trigger(eventNames, ...options) {
        // Allow a single event or an array of events
        if (!Array.isArray(eventNames)) {
            eventNames = [eventNames];
        }
        for (const name of eventNames) {
            if (this._events[name]) {
                for (const callback of [...this._events[name]]) {
                    // copy to avoid issues if callback manipulates subscriptions
                    callback(...options);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

// Example usage:

// const events = new Events();
// function onTest(a, b) { console.log('Test event:', a, b); }
// events.subscribe('test', onTest);
// events.trigger('test', 123, 456); // -> Test event: 123 456
// events.unsubscribe('test', onTest);
// events.trigger('test', 123, 456); // -> (no output)
```

**Features:**

- Multiple callbacks per event are possible.
- You can trigger multiple events at once using an array of event names.
- Parameters passed to `trigger()` after `eventNames` are forwarded to all listeners.
- Unsubscribe cleans up empty event arrays.

