Since the scores can be **very large** (up to \(10^{100}\)), you **cannot use int, long, or even long long int** in C++. Instead, you can store each score as a string and use **string addition** to sum the totals for each archer, then compare their final summed strings.

Here's a full C++ solution that **adds and compares large numbers as strings**:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

// Function to add two big numbers represented as strings
string addBigNumbers(string a, string b) {
    if (a.length() < b.length()) swap(a, b);
    int carry = 0;
    string res = "";
    int n1 = a.length(), n2 = b.length();
    for (int i = 0; i < n2; i++) {
        int sum = (a[n1-1-i]-'0') + (b[n2-1-i]-'0') + carry;
        res = char((sum%10)+'0') + res;
        carry = sum/10;
    }
    for (int i = n2; i < n1; i++) {
        int sum = (a[n1-1-i]-'0') + carry;
        res = char((sum%10)+'0') + res;
        carry = sum/10;
    }
